Arch Linux helps us to setup and maintain a Linux system;
first boot to an existing Arch Linux, which can be the live image,
  or an already installed one, with "arch-install-scripts" and "exfat-utils" packages installed,
  and a root terminal (just call "su" in a normal user's terminal);

to ensure the system clock is accurate:
; timedatectl set-ntp true

we need 2 partitions:
, +550M EFI system partition (partition type code: 1)
, and the rest for Linux system partition (the default partition type)
list disks using "fdisk -l", then use "fdisk /dev/sdx" to create the partitions:
, enter "g" command to create a GPT partition table;
, enter "n" to add a new partition;
, enter "t" to set the partition type
, enter "w" to write and exit;
format the partitions:
; mkfs.fat -F32 /dev/sdx1; mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdx2

; mount /dev/sdx2 /mnt
; mkdir /mnt/boot; mount /dev/sda1 /mnt/boot
; mkdir /mnt/etc; genfstab -U /mnt >> /mnt/etc/fstab

now you can even reuse packages previously downloaded on current system,
  by copying them to "/mnt/var/cache/pacman/pkg";
; pacstrap /mnt pacman

; arch-chroot /mnt
; pacman -S linux-lts systemd-sysvcompat intel-ucode \
  networkmanager pulseaudio-alsa udisks2 logrotate man-db nano unzip pony-stable

install "systemd-boot" bootloader:
; sh systemd-boot.sh /dev/sdx2

; useradd -m -G wheel user1
; passwd user1
; passwd

; echo -e "\n\nen_US.UTF-8 UTF-8" >> /etc/locale.gen
; locale-gen
; echo -e "LANG=en_US.UTF-8" > /etc/locale.conf

; systemctl enable systemd-timesyncd.service
; systemctl enable NetworkManager.service
; exit
; reboot

some audio devices can send and_or receive volume control signals;
  PulseAudio mutes and silences these device, by default;
so if you like you can do this:
; pactl set-sink-mute @DEFAULT_SINK@ 0
; pactl set-sink-volume @DEFAULT_SINK@ 100%

"https://www.techrapid.uk/2017/04/automatically-update-arch-linux-with-systemd.html"
"https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Systemd/Timers"
